the problem is resolution of new Date(1501713196000) is not enough.

The README link to the PERL Jira project contains a wandering '{{>}}' at the end:
{code}
Navigate to the [JIRA PERL project](https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/PERL>)
{code}

The example [GSSAPI connection string|https://metacpan.org/pod/MongoDB::MongoClient#GSSAPI-(for-Kerberos)] is missing a '{{.}}' in the server domain name:
{code}
my $mc = MongoDB::MongoClient->new(
    host =>
      'mongodb://johndoe%40EXAMPLE.COM@mongo.examplecom/?authMechanism=GSSAPI',
);
{code}

When performing repeated queries on my DB, sometimes (not everytime) I get an error that looks like this: 

{code:perl}
Use of uninitialized value $len in numeric gt (>) at /Users/jcook/perl5/perlbrew/perls/perl-5.24.1/lib/site_perl/5.24.1/darwin-2level/MongoDB/_Link.pm line 432, <$clinvar_fh> line 33668.
Use of uninitialized value $len in numeric lt (<) at /Users/jcook/perl5/perlbrew/perls/perl-5.24.1/lib/site_perl/5.24.1/darwin-2level/MongoDB/_Link.pm line 434, <$clinvar_fh> line 33668.
MongoDB::ProtocolError: response was truncated
{code}

It is always the samne line # (33668)
It is supposed to perform ~3600 queries. 

My query looks like this:


{code:perl}
        my $check_exists = $collection->find_one({
          "sections.positions.data.chromosome"      => "$chrom",
          "sections.positions.data.position"        => int($position),
          "sections.positions.data.referenceAllele" => "$reference",
          "sections.positions.data.variantAllele"   => "$alternate"
        });
{code}

$chrom is a number (eg: "2"),
$position is a plain number (eg: 12345)
$reference and $alternate are a letter (eg: "A")

I went into the file and tried to remove the troubling line, thinking it was file-specific, but it gives the exact same error. As mentioned above, the program does work sometimes (about 50%). I've done repeated find_one queries like this before so am not sure what has changed since then. 

Best, cookersjs

Hello!

Last Friday I was trying to debug some timeout issues on a coworker's computer. The client was trying to connect to a firewalled server, and timeouts weren't respected. I did some testing, and figured out it was because he has an old version of IO::Socket::IP that doesn't support the Timeout config (which was added in 0.32). I checked your code, and you recommend at least version 0.25, and check for that version in MongoDB::_Link.

I'm not sure how important it is to you guys that timeouts be supported, but it'd be nice if you updated the minimum version of IO::Socket::IP to support timeouts, or documented that timeouts may not work on older versions.

Thanks!

FWIW, here's the code I tested with:

{code}
#!/usr/bin/env perl
use strict; use warnings;
use Data::Printer;
use MongoDB;

# Connecting to this host from the wrong server is like connecting to a blackhole.
my $hostname = "mongodb://fakehostname:27017";
my $mongo = MongoDB->connect($hostname, { connect_timeout_ms => 200 });
# Force a connection.
$mongo->ns('project.Site')->find({}, { limit => 1 })->next();
print "DONE!\n";
{code}

